Appendix B – Structural Joint Analysis: Adhesive + Mechanical Interlock

B.1 Track A – Casting‑to‑Battery Joint

Geometry:

· Adhesive bond width: 20 mm, length per side: 3 200 mm → total area A_{\text{adh}} = 64 000\ \text{mm}^2.
· Four taper pins: ø12 mm (minor) – ø14 mm (major), length 25 mm, stainless 17‑4PH H900 (\tau_y = 550\ \text{MPa}).
· Shear bosses: ø20 mm, height 5 mm, machined into CFRP skin with Al ring insert.

Load cases (rigid body assumption):

1. Longitudinal shear (frontal crash):
      F_x = m_{\text{casting}} \cdot a_{\text{max}}
      Front casting mass = 18 kg, deceleration 40 g → F_x = 18 \cdot 40 \cdot 9.81 = 7 063\ \text{N}.
      Adhesive shear stress \tau_{\text{adh}} = F_x / A_{\text{adh}} = 7 063 / 64 000 = 0.11\ \text{MPa} → negligible.
      Shear pins in double shear: capacity per pin = 2 \cdot (\pi \cdot 12^2 / 4) \cdot 550 / 1000 = 124.4\ \text{kN}. Four pins → 497.6 kN.
      Interlock dominates.
2. Peeling moment (offset loading):
      Moment arm to adhesive centroid ~100 mm.
      M = F_x \cdot 0.1 = 706\ \text{Nm}.
      Peeling stress in adhesive approximated by beam on elastic foundation model. Using adhesive modulus E_{\text{adh}} = 800\ \text{MPa}, bond thickness 0.5 mm, peel stress < 5 MPa → below design limit (12 MPa).
      Mechanical interlock: pins in tension (one side) – each pin tensile capacity (\sigma_y = 1 100\ \text{MPa}):  \pi \cdot 6^2 \cdot 1100 = 124\ \text{kN}. Four pins → 498 kN, far above required.
      No adhesive peel failure expected.

Redundancy condition:
Even with 100% adhesive失效, pins + bosses provide full crash load path. Shear bosses engage before 5 mm displacement.

B.2 Track B – Extrusion‑to‑Node Joint

Joint configuration:

· Epoxy adhesive (DP460), bond gap 0.2 mm, overlap length 50 mm, width 60 mm → A_{\text{adh}} = 3 000\ \text{mm}^2 per joint.
· Blind rivets: 6.4 mm steel, 4 per joint, single shear capacity 3.2 kN each → total 12.8 kN.
· Combined stiffness: adhesive carries service loads, rivets provide fail‑safe.

Riveted joint capacity:
Max shear per joint F_{\text{rivet}} = 12.8\ \text{kN}.
Adhesive ultimate load: \tau_{\text{ult}} \cdot A_{\text{adh}} = 31 \cdot 3000 = 93\ \text{kN}.
Design limit governed by rivets (post‑adhesive failure). Safety factor 2.0 on rivet capacity → allowable 6.4 kN per joint.

Rotational stiffness:
K_\phi = \frac{M}{\theta} derived from unit load method:

K_\phi = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{E A_i e_i^2}{L_i} + \frac{G_{\text{adh}} A_{\text{adh}} t_{\text{adh}}}{h}

where e_i = distance from neutral axis to rivet i, L_i = effective length of adhered, t_{\text{adh}} = adhesive thickness.
Typical values: K_\phi \approx 8 000\ \text{Nm/deg} for bonded‑riveted configuration.

---

Appendix C – Thermal Management System: Detailed Design

C.1 Battery Immersion Cooling (Passive)

Fluid: Novec 7500 (3M) – dielectric, boiling point 128 °C, thermal conductivity 0.065 W/m·K, specific heat 1128 J/kg·K, density 1610 kg/m³.

Configuration:

· Fluid occupies 15% of free volume within pack (approx. 4.5 L).
· Cells arranged vertically; fluid fills lower 30 mm.
· Natural convection: buoyancy‑driven flow through cell gaps.
· Heat transfer coefficient (empirical correlation for vertical cylinder arrays): h \approx 150\ \text{W/m}^2\text{K} at ΔT = 10 K.

Heat rejection path:

· Heat conducted through cell sidewall → fluid → battery sidewall (Al 2 mm) → ambient air.
· Sidewall radiator: vertical fins (extruded), fin pitch 5 mm, height 40 mm, length 1400 mm, total surface area 0.8 m².
· Natural convection to ambient: h_{\text{air}} \approx 8\ \text{W/m}^2\text{K}.
· Total thermal resistance from cell to ambient: R_{\text{th}} \approx 0.45\ \text{K/W} per cell string.

Steady‑state temperature rise at 2 kW continuous heat load:
\Delta T = P \cdot R_{\text{th}} = 2000 \cdot 0.45 = 900\ \text{K} – not sustainable.
Therefore:

· Heat load limited to 800 W by limiting discharge current (C‑rate ≤ 0.5) for continuous operation.
· Peak loads (acceleration) handled by thermal capacitance: pack mass 240 kg, specific heat 900 J/kg·K → ΔT = 3 K per 100 kW·s.

C.2 Motor/Inverter Thermosiphon Oil Cooling

Oil: Shell E‑fluid E6+, thermal conductivity 0.15 W/m·K, specific heat 2000 J/kg·K.

Circuit:

· Oil sump integrated in motor housing (0.8 L).
· Electric pump (20 W, 2 L/min) activates when inverter temp > 70 °C.
· Oil flows through stator cooling channels, exits to external radiator.

Radiator:

· Aluminium, 300 × 200 × 40 mm, louvered fins.
· Natural convection capacity: 1.5 kW at ΔT = 40 K (air‑to‑oil).
· Mounted under rear floor, exposed to ram air when vehicle moves.

Thermal capacitance: Rear subframe (22 kg Al) acts as temporary heat sink; temperature rise 1 K per 20 kJ.

